courses.duties:
The Computing for Medicine program is a program run by the Department of Computer Science and the Faculty of Medicine. The program is designed to introduce medical students to programming and to the applications of computing to medicine. Students will participate in a series of bootcamp-style workshops where they will learn to program in Python and in seminars with a corresponding project on the application of computing to medicine. 
Ideally you should be available for all of the following workshop sessions:
   Sept 20, Oct 4, Oct 18, Nov 22, Dec 6:  9:30 am - 12:30 pm
   Nov 22: 1 - 4 pm
   Dec 20: 12 - 3 pm

In your application, please indicate any dates and times from these sessions when you
are unavailable. To apply for a position, applicants should send a resume/CV 
to mcraig@cs.toronto.edu  with a cc to tacoord@cs.toronto.edu.

The teaching assistants will help the instructors with facilitating the programming workshops.  
Other duties may include marking coursework.
courses.qualifications: Excellent programming skills; thorough knowledge of Python, Excellence in teaching and at least 6 months of experience teaching computer science, Excellent communication skills, Experience with applying computer science in a practical setting and broad knowledge of computer science fundamentals.

courses.duties: TA duties may include marking, leading skills development tutorials, Q&A/Exam/Assignment/Test Review sessions, and laboratories where noted.
courses.qualifications: Must be enrolled in, or have completed, an undergraduate program in computer science or education (or equivalent). Demonstrated excellent English communication skills. Patience teaching technical concepts to students with a wide variety of non-technical backgrounds. Must have completed or be in the process of completing a course involving functional programming. Must be able to write code in the Intermediate Student Language of Racket, and trace it in the same manner as the Intermediate Student Language Stepper of the DrRacket development environment.

courses.duties:
Inverted-classroom and Office Hours TA:
Attend lectures to assist in classroom activities. Prepare for each week by doing online programming activities.  Hold office hours. Mark exams. May include other tasks, such as monitoring discussion forums.

Office Hours and Marking TA:
Hold office hours. Prepare for office hours by reviewing assignments and other course materials. Mark tests and exams. May include other tasks, such as monitoring discussion forums.
courses.qualifications:
Inverted-classroom and Office Hours TA:
Experience with programming, such as by completing a 200-level CSC course, or by achieving excellent marks in multiple 100-level CSC courses, or equivalent. Experience with Python, at the level of CSC 148 or equivalent. Must be enrolled in or have completed a computer science degree, or equivalent. Must be interested in teaching beginner programmers. Willing to try different approaches when explaining simple concepts. TAs should be available during at least one of the CSC 108 lecture times (MWF10-11, MWF11-12, MWF1-2, MWF2-3, W6-9). TAs should have some availability Monday to Friday, 9am to 5pm for office hours and marking.

Office Hours and Marking TA:
Experience with programming, such as by completing a 200-level CSC course, or by achieving excellent marks in multiple 100-level CSC courses, or equivalent. Experience with Python, at the level of CSC 148 or equivalent. Must be enrolled in or have completed a computer science degree, or equivalent. Must be interested in teaching beginner programmers. TAs should have some availability Monday to Friday, 9am to 5pm for office hours and marking.

courses.duties: Attend lectures to assist in classroom activities. (Check timetable for lecture times.) Prepare for each week by doing online programming activities.  Hold office hours. Mark exams. May include other tasks, such as monitoring discussion forums.

Willing to try different approaches when explaining simple concepts. TAs should be available during at least one of the CSC 108 lecture times (MWF10-11, MWF11-12, MWF1-2, MWF2-3, W6-9). TAs should have some availability Monday to Friday, 9am to 5pm for office hours and marking.

TA duties may include marking, leading skills development tutorials, Q&A/Exam/Assignment/Test Review
sessions, and laboratories where noted.
courses.qualifications: Qualifications: Excellent programming skills and experience with programming in Python. Full understanding of the Python memory and execution models. Deep understanding of fundamental computer science concepts such as recursion, searching, sorting, and complexity analysis. Excellent communication skills.

courses.duties: TA duties may include marking, leading skills development tutorials, Q&A/Exam/Assignment/Test Review sessions, and laboratories where noted.
courses.qualifications: Experience and interest in machine learning, as evidenced by research work in the area and/or excellent performance in university courses in machine learning and neural networks such as CSC411/2515. Thorough understanding of the fundamentals of machine learning, including a thorough understanding of the fundamental mathematical and computational techniques used in CSC411, such as gradient descent, eigendecomposition of matrices, and basic probability theory. Experience with deep learning and/or reinforcement learning preferred. Ability to communicate complex ideas clearly. Excellent programming skills; extensive experience working in a scientific computing framework such as SciPy/NumPy or MATLAB; familiarity with Python.

courses.duties: TA duties may include marking, leading skills development tutorials, Q&A/Exam/Assignment/Test Review sessions, and laboratories where noted.
courses.qualifications: Thorough knowledge of theory and implementation of databases: A or higher in graduate level DB course (such as CSC2509/2525/2531) and equivalent of A- or higher in advanced OS course (such as CSC469/2208). Desirable: C/C++ and Java.

courses.duties: Marking 3 tests and 1 exam; presenting solutions to example problems; answering questions
courses.qualifications: A thorough knowledge of formal methods of software design. Active research in formal methods. A grade of A- or higher in CSC465 or CSC2104 or equivalent.

applicants.course_preferences: C4M101H1F, CSC108H1F-A, CSC104H1F, CSC104H1S, CSC108H1F, CSC411H1F/2515HF
